What did you do on your summer vacation?
Over the past couple of months, Debra McCosco, a Liberty Elementary recess monitor, lovingly made nearly 900 (❤️900!!!❤️) cloth face masks in all sizes and designs, and today she donated her bright and cheerful creations to the Elementary school.
That's her in bright blue, photographed with Principal Harris, Dr. MacKrell, Mrs. Bury, Miss Ellmauer, Ms. Vasta, Mrs. DiSanto and Mrs. Blais.
We are so #LibertyProud and grateful to Ms. McCosco. Please join us in thanking her!

Hunger Solutions New York
July 1 at 12:28 PM ·

Pandemic-EBT food benefits will be issued automatically to families whose child(ren) received free or reduced-price lunch at school through the federal lunch program. This includes all students who attend a school that provides free meals for all. Each child will receive $420 on a new or existing EBT card that can be used like a bank debit card to purchase food from participating stores. P-EBT benefits are not limited by immigration status and public charge rules do NOT apply.

Learn more: hungersolutionsny.org/pebt

Each year Liberty High School presents athletic awards for all three seasons during the Athletic Block L Awards presentation. This celebration also includes special wards given to underclassmen and to Seniors.

Unfortunately, this year the awards could not be presented in person but the Liberty coaching staff created videos for the wards for each team. These videos were knitted together into one presentation. Since the spring season was cancelled the coaches were also asked to make a few brief comments for the "season that wasn't".

Even though the awards could not be made in person to the athletes, these young men and women still deserve all the recognition and credit for their achievements. Honor them by watching the video!

post_text:
Picking up your cap and gown is always a big deal, but this year Liberty made this right of passage a full-fledged, blast-the-music, no-holds-barred, Mr. Adams-is-bringing-his-air-horn kind of event!

As students stopped by Friday evening for their graduation gowns they were greeted by scores of their teachers and school staffers, most of whom they haven’t seen IRL since mid-March. The bus lane became a parade route, and the Class of 2020 was met with cheers, applause, smiles and an outpouring of love easily felt across any (social) distance.
#LibertyPride

post_text:
We are pleased to announce that the Liberty Central School District has been recognized by the National Association for Music Merchants as one of the the "Best Communities for Music Education!"

The Best Communities for Music Education program evaluates schools and districts based on funding, staffing of highly-qualified teachers, commitment to standards, and access to music instruction.

Please join us in thanking our music teachers!

We still have plenty of Growing Hope kits available for Liberty students, so please stop by the High School tomorrow (Thursday, May 6) from 9-11 a.m!
The kits, which are a special gift from our generous friends at Bethel Woods, include a clay pot to decorate, paint, a brush, seeds and soil, and are designed so even young students can enjoy success.
Look for the Growing Kits right next to our student meal distribution table near the High School loading dock. Quantities are limited, so one per student, please.

Tomorrow (Wednesday, May 6) you can pick up one of these Growing Hope flower kits, a special gift from our friends at Bethel Woods Center for the Arts.
The kits include a clay pot, paint, brushes, seeds and soil, and are designed so young students can enjoy success. Later in the year, Bethel Woods will invite student gardeners back to the historic site for a planting of a peace garden on the festival field.
The kits will be available to Liberty Central School District students 9-11 a.m. at the High School, right by our student meal table.
Supplies are limited. One per child, please.

These recent weeks have been difficult ones for everyone. The time is unprecedented, the demands often overwhelming, and the unknowns equally as unsettling. The LCSD School Counselors, Social Workers, and School Psychologists want to remind you that we are here for you and always available to provide social and emotional support and resources.
Call 292-5400, ext. 5112 or visit our website for contact information at each grade level: https://www.libertyk12.org/this-is-hard-libertys-counselors-are-here-for-you/

The Liberty Middle School Student Council can't hold regular meetings right now, but these resourceful students and their advisors are still staying connected.
The students, along with Mrs. Murphy and Mr. Golden, recently got together for a rousing game of Scattergories! It was a terrific success, and more virtual game nights are in the works.
So, can you name a great place starting with the letter "L," where the students, teachers and staff are always there for one another?
We sure can.
#LibertyPride

Volunteers are still needed to staff two childcare centers for the children of essential workers. Several Liberty families have requested this service, which provides free childcare to support the critical work of healthcare workers and first responders as we contend with the COVID-19 pandemic.

County school districts are working with the Sullivan County Child Care Council, Sullivan County Government, SUNY Sullivan and Sullivan BOCES to provide this service

There are two childcare locations, SUNY Sullivan in Loch Sheldrake and the Catskill Regional Medical Center. If you can volunteer, please fill out this survey: https://bit.ly/childcare_volunteers.

If you were unable to pick up your child’s school work packet, here's how the district will get it to you:

* ELEMENTARY: Packets will be mailed (Grades K-4)
* MIDDLE SCHOOL: Packets will be mailed (Grades 5/6).
For students using Google Classroom, the teachers' letters and assignments will be mailed (Grades 7/8). Students should also monitor their email for Google Classroom updates.
If you need a vital item from LMS (i.e. a Chromebook, medication, or instrument) call 845-292-5400 ext. 2302
* HIGH SCHOOL: If you are unable to pick up school work not available on Google Classroom, or if you cannot access Google Classroom, please call 845-292-5400 ext. 2002.

post_text: PARENTS and GUARDIANS: If you were unable to pick up your child’s academic work packet, please be assured that we are working on a plan to get it delivered to you as soon as possible. We will announce those details shortly.
text: PARENTS and GUARDIANS: If you were unable to pick up your child’s academic work packet, please be assured that we are working on a plan to get it delivered to you as soon as possible. We will announce those details shortly.

post_text:
REMINDER: This is a reminder that packets of academic work will be available for pick up 9 a.m. - 3 p.m. TODAY, Thursday, March 19, at the Elementary, Middle and High schools.

Please stop by your child’s school during those hours to pick up their packet. School is closed through April 3, and today is the last opportunity for pick-up.

WE ARE CLOSED UNTIL APRIL 3

Sullivan County Manager Josh Potosek tonight has issued an emergency order closing all schools, including the Liberty Central School District, now through April 3.

Given that this is a rapidly evolving public health issue, school leaders have decided that this is the most prudent action available to limit the spread of COVID-19.

As the coronavirus continues to disrupt our day-to-day lives, the topmost priority of the district remains steady: To keep our students and staff healthy and safe.

We will provide further updates soon regarding student work and meals. As always, we appreciate your patience and understanding.

post_text:
We are so #LibertyProud of our National Honor Society, which this month completed a service project which will help scores of people escaping unstable domestic situations.The students collected much needed personal care items - shampoo, deodorant, toothpaste, and other toiletries - from LCSD offices, New Hope and Rolling V throughout January.
In all, 11 boxes were filled to the brim, which were then donated to Fearless Hudson Valley (formerly Safe Homes of Orange County) for distribution to their clients, who often flee dangerous situations with nothing. Seniors and the Student Council also assisted in the effort.
Please join us in thanking these students for their good work.

The Grade 6 Breakfast will be held 9 a.m. Thursday.

Good evening parents and guardians!
We hope everyone has stayed safe and warm during the storm. We anticipate that some folks may still be getting out from under the snow tomorrow morning, so our Grade 5 and Grade 6 Honor Roll Breakfasts have been rescheduled to Thursday, Dec. 5.

post_text:
‪For 47 years, Asst. Cook Dottie Davison has been a welcoming face on the lunch line, serving an estimated 4.5 million meals (and countless from-scratch peanut butter cookies) to our students.
Today was her last day, and staff and students gathered in the high school cafeteria to wish her a happy retirement and present her with her very own Liberty letterman jacket. A plaque honoring Mrs. Davison will also be hung in the cafeteria honoring her limitless commitment to our students.
Always generous, she even shared her famous Liberty Cookie recipe, though we suspect few will be able to match Mrs. Davison's baking skills. You can find the recipe on the district website:
at https://www.libertyk12.org/dottie-davison-beloved-asst-cook-retires-after-47-years/
Please join us in wishing her well.

post_text:
It's impossible to adequately express our gratitude to our local first responders. They are our dads, moms, spouses, siblings and neighbors - and some are even Liberty High School students - who come running when we need them most. And that, after all, is the very definition of a hero.
On Friday, members of the Liberty Fire Department, the Swan Lake Fire District, the White Sulphur Springs Fire Department and Mobil Medic were here for our Liberty Middle School students, teaching them how to stay safe and, we suspect, inspiring a few of them to grow up to be heroes, too.
Two words will never be enough, but we'll say it anyway:
Thank you.

shared_text:
Tri-Valley Central School District
October 2, 2019 at 1:45 PM ·

Please join us 7-8:30 p.m. Wednesday, Oct. 9 for “Sweethearts and Heroes,” a special presentation about the impact of bullying on schools, neighborhoods, and individuals.
Through knowledge and communication, “Sweethearts and Heroes” delivers a powerful message of bystander empowerment, empathy and leadership to all audiences, including K-12 students, parents and communities. We all have the potential to be someone’s hero.
The free event will be held in the Bernstein Theater, Tri-Valley Secondary School, 34 Moore Hill Road, Grahamsville. Childcare will be provided.

A big Liberty thank you to Tiffany and Josh Hafler from M&M Auto Group and everyone who participated in this summer's Ford Drive 4 UR School fundraiser. Today, M&M Auto stopped by the Elementary School with a $3,300 donation raised at the event!

Principal Jacqueline Harris and LES Building Leadership teachers Rachel Countryman and Amanda Kehrley, who helped organize the fundraiser, accepted the check along with some of our wonderful students.

The donation will go long way towards student activities and equipment geared toward physical and emotional wellness, and we couldn't be more grateful!

A big Liberty thank you to Tiffany and Josh Hafler from M&M Auto Group and everyone who participated in this summer's Ford Drive 4 UR School fundraiser. Today, M&M Auto stopped by the Elementary School with a $3,300 donation raised at the event!

Principal Jacqueline Harris and LES Building Leadership teachers Rachel Countryman and Amanda Kehrley, who helped organize the fundraiser, accepted the check along with some of our wonderful students.

The donation will go long way towards student activities and equipment geared toward physical and emotional wellness, and we couldn't be more grateful!

post_text: Congratulations to the Girls JV Soccer team on their win against SS Seward 4-0. Scoring for Liberty were Alicia Edwards (1) & Sophia Jastrzebski (3) with a hat-trick. Assisting those goals today were Hennesi Rebolledo & Julia Gorr. Creating many plays and opportunities on the field were midfielders Aneliya Carrion, Summer Schmidt, Alli Dworetsky, and Joseline Flores. Holding down the defense with style were defenders Dianna Marty, Brianna Niforos, Angelina Rodriguez, Victoria Hinkley, & Emily Lutz. Keeper Charlyanna Johnson had a shutout game, leaving Liberty victorious tonight! These ladies played one classy game!

Today at 8:46 a.m. all Liberty Central Schools were still as students and staff observed a moment of silence for those who died on Sept. 11, 2001.
This American flag, displayed in the Middle School, is signed with expressions of gratitude and promises to never forget.
